lder\":\"Content…\",\"fontSize\":\"small\"} -->\n<p class=\"has-drop-cap has-small-font-size\">I am a Ph.D. student of <a href=\"https://www.cs.mcgill.ca/~dprecup/\">Doina Precup</a>&nbsp;and <a href=\"https://mila.quebec/yoshua-bengio/\">Yoshua Bengio</a>, at&nbsp;<a href=\"http://cs.mcgill.ca/\">School of Computer Science</a>&nbsp;of&nbsp;<a href=\"https://mcgill.ca/\">McGill University</a>. In summer 2020, I graduated as a MSc., under the supervision of <a href=\"https://www.cs.mcgill.ca/~dprecup/\">Doina Precup</a>&nbsp;and <a href=\"https://www.cs.mcgill.ca/~chang/\">Xiao-Wen Chang</a>, with CGPA 4.0/4.0.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph --></div></div>\n<!-- /wp:media-text -->\n\n<!-- wp:media-text {\"mediaPosition\":\"right\",\"mediaId\":244,\"mediaLink\":\"http://localhost/homepage/the-new-umoma-opens-its-doors-2/logo-frq-couleur-1/\",\"mediaType\":\"image\",\"mediaWidth\":23,\"mediaSizeSlug\":\"full\"} -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-media-text alignwide has-media-on-the-right is-stacked-on-mobile\" style=\"grid-template-columns:auto 23%\"><figure class=\"wp-block-media-text__media\"><img src=\"http://localhost/homepage/wp-content/uploads/2021/06/logo-frq-couleur-1.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-244 size-full\"/></figure><div class=\"wp-block-media-text__content\"><!-- wp:paragraph {\"dropCap\":true,\"placeholder\":\"Content…\",\"fontSize\":\"small\"} -->\n<p class=\"has-drop-cap has-small-font-size\">I am a recipient of the <a href=\"https://frq.gouv.qc.ca/en/\" data-type=\"URL\" data-id=\"https://frq.gouv.qc.ca/en/\">FRQ (Nature and Technologies)</a> funds, ranked<strong> <span class=\"has-inline-color has-accent-color\">1st </span></strong>among all contenders. </p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph --></div></div>\n<!-- /wp:media-text -->\n\n<!-- wp:media-text {\"mediaPosition\":\"right\",\"mediaId\":74,\"mediaLink\":\"http://localhost/homepage/the-new-umoma-opens-its-doors-2/dlut_logo/\",\"mediaType\":\"image\",\"mediaWidth\":23,\"mediaSizeSlug\":\"full\"} -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-media-text alignwide has-media-on-the-right is-stacked-on-mobile\" style=\"grid-template-columns:auto 23%\"><figure class=\"wp-block-media-text__media\"><img src=\"http://localhost/homepage/wp-content/uploads/2020/06/DLUT_logo.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-74 size-full\"/></figure><div class=\"wp-block-media-text__content\"><!-- wp:paragraph {\"dropCap\":true,\"placeholder\":\"Content…\",\"fontSize\":\"small\"} -->\n<p class=\"has-drop-cap has-small-font-size\">I finished my undergrad at <a href=\"https://en.dlut.edu.cn/\">Dalian University of Technology</a>, with major in Computer Science and Technology, and minor in Creative Practices (robotics). I received the Outstanding Student Researcher award of class 2018 and graduated with 90+ percentage (CGPA 4.0/4.0).</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph --></div></div>\n<!-- /wp:media-text -->\n\n<!-- wp:media-text {\"mediaPosition\":\"right\",\"mediaId\":238,\"mediaLink\":\"http://localhost/homepage/the-new-umoma-opens-its-doors-2/saxophone-brass-blow-jazz-instrument-512/\",\"mediaType\":\"image\",\"mediaWidth\":23,\"mediaSizeSlug\":\"full\"} -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-media-text alignwide has-media-on-the-right is-stacked-on-mobile\" style=\"grid-template-columns:auto 23%\"><figure class=\"wp-block-media-text__media\"><img src=\"http://localhost/homepage/wp-content/uploads/2021/06/saxophone-brass-blow-jazz-instrument-512.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-238 size-full\"/></figure><div class=\"wp-block-media-text__content\"><!-- wp:paragraph {\"dropCap\":true,\"placeholder\":\"Content…\",\"fontSize\":\"small\"} -->\n<p class=\"has-drop-cap has-small-font-size\">I had been studying saxophone performance, before switching to science &amp; engineering.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph --></div></div>\n<!-- /wp:media-text --></div>\n<!-- /wp:column --></div>\n<!-- /wp:columns --></div>\n<!-- /wp:group -->', 'DISCOVERING INTELLIGENCE VIA COMPUTATION', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '36-revision-v1', '', '', '2021-09-04 14:59:53', '2021-09-04 18:59:53', '', 36, 'http://localhost/homepage/?p=274', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(277, 1, '2021-09-04 15:10:18', '2021-09-04 19:10:18', '<!-- wp:image {\"id\":192,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\",\"linkDestination\":\"custom\"} -->\n<figure class=\"wp-block-image size-large\"><a href=\"http://mingde.world/publications/a-step-towards-conscious-planning/\"><img src=\"http://localhost/homepage/wp-content/uploads/2021/06/CP.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-192\"/></a><figcaption><span class=\"has-inline-color has-accent-color\"><em>Recent work featuring conscious bottleneck for Model-Based Reinforcement Learning</em></span>: <em>A Consciousness-Inspired Planning Agent for Model-Based Reinforcement Learning</em></figcaption></figure>\n<!-- /wp:image -->', 'Conscious Planning Publication Block', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '197-revision-v1', '', '', '2021-09-04 15:10:18', '2021-09-04 19:10:18', '', 197, 'http://localhost/homepage/?p=277', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(280, 1, '2021-09-04 17:59:41', '2021-09-04 21:59:41', '<!-- wp:paragraph {\"align\":\"center\",\"fontSize\":\"larger\"} -->\n<p class=\"has-text-align-center has-larger-font-size\"><span class=\"has-inline-color has-accent-color\"><strong>A Consciousness-Inspired Planning Agent for Model-Based Reinforcement Learning</strong></span></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph {\"align\":\"center\",\"fontSize\":\"small\"} -->\n<p class=\"has-text-align-center has-small-font-size\">Mingde Zhao, Zhen Liu, Sitao Luan, Shuyuan Zhang, Doina Precup, Yoshua Bengio</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph {\"align\":\"center\"} -->\n<p class=\"has-text-align-center\">(<a href=\"https://arxiv.org/abs/2106.02097\" data-type=\"URL\" data-id=\"https://arxiv.org/abs/2106.02097\">arXiv</a> / <a href=\"https://github.com/PwnerHarry/CP\" data-type=\"URL\" data-id=\"https://github.com/PwnerHarry/CP\">GitHub</a>)</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph {\"dropCap\":true,\"fontSize\":\"large\"} -->\n<p class=\"has-drop-cap has-large-font-size\">We introduce into reinforcement learning inductive biases inspired by higher-order cognitive functions in humans. These architectural constraints enable the planning to direct attention dynamically to the interesting parts of the state at each step of imagined future trajectories.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Whether when planning our paths home from the office or from a hotel to an airport in an unfamiliar city, we typically focus on a small subset of relevant variables, e.g. the change in position or the presence of traffic. An interesting hypothesis of how this path planning skill generalizes across scenarios is that it may be due to computation associated with the conscious processing of information. Conscious attention focuses on a few necessary environment elements, with the help of an internal abstract representation of the world. This pattern, also known as consciousness in the first sense (C1), has been theorized to enable humans’ exceptional adaptability and learning efficiency. A central characterization of conscious processing is that it involves a bottleneck, which forces one to handle dependencies between very few characteristics of the environment at a time. Though this focus on a small subset of the available information may seem limiting, it may facilitate Out-Of-Distribution (OOD) and systematic generalization toother situations where the ignored variables are different and yet still irrelevant. In this paper, we propose an architecture which allows us to encode some of these ideas into reinforcement learning agents.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Our proposal is to take inspiration from human consciousness to build an architecture which learns a useful state space and in which attention can be focused on a small set of variables at any time. This idea of “partial planning” is enabled by modern deep RL techniques. Specifically, we propose an end-to-end latent-space MBRL agent which does not require reconstructing the observations, as in most existing works, and uses Model Predictive Control (MPC) for decision-time planning. From an observation, the agent encodes a set of objects as a state, with a selective attention bottleneck mechanism to plan over selected subsets of the state (Sec. 4). Our experiments show that the inductive biases improve a specific form of OOD generalization, where consistent dynamics are preserved across seemingly different environment settings (Sec. 5).</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"align\":\"center\",\"id\":229,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\"><figure class=\"aligncenter size-large\"><img src=\"http://localhost/homepage/wp-content/uploads/2021/06/image.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-229\"/><figcaption><em>Experiment showing the promising OOD generalization ability of the bottleneck</em></figcaption></figure></div>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong><span class=\"has-inline-color has-accent-color\">Interesting Q &amp; As:</span></strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Q: Can you define what you mean by OOD in this work?</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>A: We focus on skills <em>transferrable</em> to totally different environments with <em>consistent dynamics</em>. This means the environmental dynamics that is sufficient for solving the in-distribution training tasks and the OOD evaluation tasks are consistently preserved, while the rest can be very different. Intuitively, we want to train our agent to be able to plan routes in the home city and expect this ability to be generalized to totally different municipality. The places can be very different, but the route planning skill depends on the knowledge that is quite universal.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Q: Why do you employ a non-static setting where environments change every episode?</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>A: Intuitively, the agent has no need to understand the dynamics of the task if the environment is fixed. Learning to memorize where to go and where not to is far easier than reasoning about what may happen. With the challenges, it became necessity for the agent to indeed learn and understand the environment dynamics, which is crucial for OOD evaluation.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Q: Why not use richer architectures for experiments?</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>A: Since there are already many components in the proposed agent, to isolate possible factors that would influence the agent behaviors, we use the minimal architecture sizes that marginally enables good RL performance on our test settings.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Q: Why not use MCTS as the search method for decision-time planning?</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>A: Unlike AlphaGo, which employs MCTS, our architecture is based on the simplest baseline DQN. DQN uses a value-estimator based greedy policy instead of a parameterized one as the actor-critic architecture used in AlphaGo. The DQN policy is deterministic <em>w.r.t.</em> the estimated values therefore the planning cannot take sufficient advantage of the sample based MCTS.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"align\":\"center\",\"id\":233,\"width\":610,\"height\":565,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\"><figure class=\"aligncenter size-large is-resized\"><img src=\"http://localhost/homepage/wp-content/uploads/2021/06/image-1.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-233\" width=\"610\" height=\"565\"/><figcaption><em>A birdseye view of the overall design</em></figcaption></figure></div>\n<!-- /wp:image -->', 'A Step Towards Conscious Planning', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '205-revision-v1', '', '', '2021-09-04 17:59:41', '2021-09-04 21:59:41', '', 205, 'http://localhost/homepage/?p=280', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
(279, 1, '2021-09-04 17:58:50', '2021-09-04 21:58:50', '<!-- wp:paragraph {\"align\":\"center\",\"fontSize\":\"larger\"} -->\n<p class=\"has-text-align-center has-larger-font-size\"><span class=\"has-inline-color has-accent-color\"><strong>A Consciousness-Inspired Planning Agent for Model-Based Reinforcement Learning</strong></span></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph {\"align\":\"center\",\"fontSize\":\"small\"} -->\n<p class=\"has-text-align-center has-small-font-size\">Mingde Zhao, Zhen Liu, Sitao Luan, Shuyuan Zhang, Doina Precup, Yoshua Bengio</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph {\"align\":\"center\"} -->\n<p class=\"has-text-align-center\">(<a href=\"https://arxiv.org/abs/2106.02097\" data-type=\"URL\" data-id=\"https://arxiv.org/abs/2106.02097\">arXiv</a> / <a href=\"https://github.com/PwnerHarry/CP\" data-type=\"URL\" data-id=\"https://github.com/PwnerHarry/CP\">GitHub</a>)</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph {\"dropCap\":true,\"fontSize\":\"large\"} -->\n<p class=\"has-drop-cap has-large-font-size\">We introduce into reinforcement learning inductive biases inspired by higher-order cognitive functions in humans. These architectural constraints enable the planning to direct attention dynamically to the interesting parts of the state at each step of imagined future trajectories.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Whether when planning our paths home from the office or from a hotel to an airport in an unfamiliar city, we typically focus on a small subset of relevant variables, e.g. the change in position or the presence of traffic. An interesting hypothesis of how this path planning skill generalizes across scenarios is that it may be due to computation associated with the conscious processing of information. Conscious attention focuses on a few necessary environment elements, with the help of an internal abstract representation of the world. This pattern, also known as consciousness in the first sense (C1), has been theorized to enable humans’ exceptional adaptability and learning efficiency. A central characterization of conscious processing is that it involves a bottleneck, which forces one to handle dependencies between very few characteristics of the environment at a time. Though this focus on a small subset of the available information may seem limiting, it may facilitate Out-Of-Distribution (OOD) and systematic generalization toother situations where the ignored variables are different and yet still irrelevant. In this paper, we propose an architecture which allows us to encode some of these ideas into reinforcement learning agents.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>Our proposal is to take inspiration from human consciousness to build an architecture which learns a useful state space and in which attention can be focused on a small set of variables at any time. This idea of “partial planning” is enabled by modern deep RL techniques. Specifically, we propose an end-to-end latent-space MBRL agent which does not require reconstructing the observations, as in most existing works, and uses Model Predictive Control (MPC) for decision-time planning. From an observation, the agent encodes a set of objects as a state, with a selective attention bottleneck mechanism to plan over selected subsets of the state (Sec. 4). Our experiments show that the inductive biases improve a specific form of OOD generalization, where consistent dynamics are preserved across seemingly different environment settings (Sec. 5).</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"align\":\"center\",\"id\":229,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\"><figure class=\"aligncenter size-large\"><img src=\"http://localhost/homepage/wp-content/uploads/2021/06/image.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-229\"/><figcaption><em>Experiment showing the promising OOD generalization ability of the bottleneck</em></figcaption></figure></div>\n<!-- /wp:image -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong><span class=\"has-inline-color has-accent-color\">Interesting Q &amp; As:</span></strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Q: Can you define what you mean by OOD in this work?</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>A: We focus on skills <em>transferrable</em> to totally different environments with <em>consistent dynamics</em>. This means the environmental dynamics that is sufficient for solving the in-distribution training tasks and the OOD evaluation tasks are consistently preserved, while the rest can be very different. Intuitively, we want to train our agent to be able to plan routes in the home city and expect this ability to be generalized to totally different municipality. The places can be very different, but the route planning skill depends on the knowledge that is quite universal.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Q: Why do you employ a non-static setting where environments change every episode?</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>A: Intuitively, the agent has no need to understand the dynamics of the task if the environment is fixed. Learning to memorize where to go and where not to is far easier than reasoning about what may happen. With the challenges, it became necessity for the agent to indeed learn and understand the environment dynamics, which is crucial for OOD evaluation.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Q: Why not use deeper architectures for experiments?</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>A: Since there are already many components in the proposed agent, to isolate possible factors that would influence the agent behaviors, we use the minimal architecture sizes that marginally enables good RL performance on our test settings.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p><strong>Q: Why not use MCTS as the search method for decision-time planning?</strong></p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:paragraph -->\n<p>A: Unlike AlphaGo, which employs MCTS, our architecture is based on the simplest baseline DQN. DQN uses a value-estimator based greedy policy instead of a parameterized one as the actor-critic architecture used in AlphaGo. The DQN policy is deterministic <em>w.r.t.</em> the estimated values therefore the planning cannot take sufficient advantage of the sample based MCTS.</p>\n<!-- /wp:paragraph -->\n\n<!-- wp:image {\"align\":\"center\",\"id\":233,\"width\":610,\"height\":565,\"sizeSlug\":\"large\",\"linkDestination\":\"none\"} -->\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\"><figure class=\"aligncenter size-large is-resized\"><img src=\"http://localhost/homepage/wp-content/uploads/2021/06/image-1.png\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-233\" width=\"610\" height=\"565\"/><figcaption><em>A birdseye view of the overall design</em></figcaption></figure></div>\n<!-- /wp:image -->', 'A Step Towards Conscious Planning', '', 'inherit', 'closed', 'closed', '', '205-revision-v1', '', '', '2021-09-04 17:58:50', '2021-09-04 21:58:50', '', 205, 'http://localhost/homepage/?p=279', 0, 'revision', '', 0),
